d10 1
a10 1
<b> %TOPIC% (aka TCAO) helps you content in your wiki.  by classifying topics according to their _function_ and/or _subject matter._ </b> It also provides a user-friendly interface for creating new topics that automatically incorporates this classification system. Together, these basic elements provide a platform that allow you to create any number of simple TWikiApplications.
d12 8
a19 25
%TOPIC% organizes topics using two primary classifications:
   * *TopicTypes* group topics according to their __function or purpose.__ Some examples of <nop>TopicTypes include <nop>WebLog, <nop>MeetingNote, <nop>DiscussionTopic, or <nop>ReferenceNote. Oftentimes, <nop>TopicType have a characteristic structure which can be defined by a "[[TWiki.TWikiTemplates#Template_Topics][template topic]]".
   * *SubjectAreas* group topics according to __the subject matter__ of the topic. Examples might include <nop>FamilyAndFriends, <nop>WorldPolitics, <nop>WebDesign, or <nop>OpenSourceMovement. 

A special topic called *<nop>CreateNewTopic* provides a simple interface for creating new topics using this topic classification scheme and draws in special form elements relevant to the particular <nop>TopicType the user chooses from a drop-down menu. It also displays a list of all the topics of the particular <nop>TopicType the user selects to help reduce chances of creating two topics with nearly identical names.

The TopicClassificationAddOn installation includes some special topics which facilitate the creation of new <nop>TopicTypes and <nop>SubjectAreas and can serve as examples for developing your own classifications and simple TWiki:Codev.TWikiApplications. These include:
   * *<nop>TopicClassification* offers an overview of the TopicClassificationAddOn for the particular web in which it's used, including a list of all the <nop>TopicTypes and <nop>SubjectAreas.
   * *<nop>TopicTypeTemplate* that's automatically assigned to new <nop>TopicTypes. It includes ability to filter that <nop>TopicType but <nop>SubjectArea. For example, you could see all <nop>ReferenceTopics related to <nop>WebDesign.
   * Likewise there's a *<nop>SubjectAreaTemplate* that's assigned to new <nop>SubjectArea topics that offers ability to filter by <nop>TopicType.
   * One <nop>TopicType that is almost universally useful, <nop>ReferenceTopic, is included as an example <nop>TopicType.
   * A *<nop>WebFormWithClassification* topic that you can use as a template for your <nop>WebForm.
   * *<nop>TopicHeadline* explains this field that is used in <nop>WebFormWithClassification for displaying summaries of topics.

---++ Usage

   * The <nop>TopicClassification topic provides an entry-point for the topic classification system as applied in the particular web where it's installed.
   * The <nop>TopicType topic is really the core of the TopicClassificationAddOn. From here you can:
      * Define new <nop>TopicTypes using the "Create New <nop>TopicType" form near the bottom of the page. 
      * List your <nop>TopicTypes in a form at the beginning of the topic which populates the <nop>TopicType field in WebForm. Note: Since TWiki can not yet generate these forms dynamically, you need to manually add new <nop>TopicTypes to this form.
      * After you have created a new <nop>TopicType, there a a couple additional options for customizing how it's used:
         * On your new TopicType topic, notice there is link to define a template for that TopicType. If you create this template, any new topics you assign to this <nop>TopicType will automatically incorporate this template.
         * If you edit your new TopicType topic, you will see there are some hidden html-form elements. When you select this <nop>TopicType from the drop-down menu in <nop>CreateNewTopic, these form elements will be displayed there for additional user input. You can modify these or add new form elements to match the template for your new <nop>TopicType. For more information about how to insert data entered in an html-form into a TWiki topic template, see TWiki/TWikiTemplates#Template_Topics_in_Action.
   * <nop>SubjectAreas are actually just another <nop>TopicType, however they have special status as a secondary classification scheme. New <nop>SubjectAreas can be created from the <nop>CreateNewTopic topic.
   * The <nop>CreateNewTopic is used to, you guessed it, create new topics using the classification system. It includes a drop down menu of all the <nop>TopicTypes which, upon selecting a <nop>TopicType, will add any special form elements you have defined for that particular <nop>TopicType. If you place ==%<nop>INCLUDE{CreateNewTopic}%== within another topic or skin or navigation menu, it will display the same drop down menu of <nop>TopicTypes which, upon selecting a <nop>TopicType, will jump you to the <nop>CreateNewTopic topic with all the appropriate form elements for that <nop>TopicType displayed.
